# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Deterministic line endings across Windows / Linux / macOS checkouts.
#
# Why this file exists: Git for Windows ships `core.autocrlf=true` in its
# SYSTEM gitconfig, so a Windows checkout writes CRLF into the working tree
# while Biome's formatter expects LF. Result: `pnpm lint` reports formatter
# errors on Windows and passes on Linux CI — the same commit, two verdicts.
#
# `eol=lf` takes precedence over `core.autocrlf`, so this pins LF in every
# working tree on every OS without anyone editing their git config. The
# repository index is already 100% LF (verified: `git ls-files --eol` →
# 562/562 `i/lf`), so this changes no committed content — it only stops
# future checkouts and future writes from drifting.
#
# NOTE: adding this file does NOT rewrite files already sitting on disk as
# CRLF. To normalize an existing working tree (produces no git diff):
#     git add --renormalize .
#     git checkout-index --force --all
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Default: detect text, and always check it out with LF.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Explicit for the toolchain-sensitive types Biome formats.
*.ts    text eol=lf
*.tsx   text eol=lf
*.js    text eol=lf
*.jsx   text eol=lf
*.mjs   text eol=lf
*.cjs   text eol=lf
*.json  text eol=lf
*.jsonc text eol=lf
*.css   text eol=lf
*.md    text eol=lf
*.yml   text eol=lf
*.yaml  text eol=lf
*.html  text eol=lf
*.svg   text eol=lf

# Shell scripts MUST be LF or they will not execute in Linux containers/CI.
*.sh        text eol=lf
Dockerfile  text eol=lf
*.dockerfile text eol=lf

# Generated: LF, and keep it out of language stats / review noise.
pnpm-lock.yaml text eol=lf linguist-generated=true

# Binaries — never transform the bytes.
*.png  binary
*.jpg  binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif  binary
*.ico  binary
*.webp binary
*.avif binary
*.pdf  binary
*.woff binary
*.woff2 binary
*.ttf  binary
*.eot  binary
*.otf  binary
*.mp4  binary
*.webm binary
*.zip  binary
*.gz   binary
